SUMMARY:Discovery Series\, Dr. Bruce Maxwell\, Teaching Professor & Director of Computing Programs\, Northeastern University Seattle
DESCRIPTION:What if the way we prepare images for computers is getting in the way of understanding them?\nMost digital images are designed to look good to human eyes. But what’s best for people isn’t always best for machines. Bruce Maxwell\, teaching professor at Northeastern University’s Seattle campus\, explores how rethinking image formats—especially how brightness and color are represented—can unlock new capabilities in computer vision. \n​Inspired by how the human eye processes light\, Maxwell’s research shows that using alternative formats can make AI models more stable under changing lighting\, reveal hidden patterns\, and improve performance across tasks like object recognition and image generation. His experiments suggest that small changes in how we feed images to machines can lead to big improvements in how they interpret the world. \n​This talk invites us to look beneath the surface of everyday images—and discover how seeing differently might help machines see better. \n​About the Discovery Series: designed to bring together the state’s preeminent researchers\, innovative leaders\, and elected officials who want to stay on top of important advancements being made in our state\, each Discovery Series program includes lunch\, networking time\, a Q&A session\, and an opportunity to meet the speaker.
URL:https://www.geekwire.com/calendar-event/discovery-series-dr-bruce-maxwell-teaching-professor-director-of-computing-programs-northeastern-university-seattle/
LOCATION:McKinsey & Company\, 1420 5th Avenue\, Suite 4300\, Seattle\, 98101\, United States
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://cdn.geekwire.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/discoveryseries_drbrucemaxwell.jpg
END:VEVENT
